10280nam a22010815i 9780228002574DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280025747 a10.1515/97802280025742doi  a(DE-B1597)657829  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV640.5.S97 7aSOC0660002bisacsh04a305.922302aA National Project :bSyrian Refugee Resettlement in Canada /ced. by Margaret Walton-Roberts, Leah K. Hamilton, Luisa Veronis. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource :b9 tables, 1 diagram  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Refugee and Forced Migration Studies ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote about the Cover -- tA National Project: Exploring Canadian Exceptionalism in Refugee Resettlement -- tPerspectives of Syrian Refugees -- tSyrian Refugees' Experiences with Resettlement, Reception, and Integration -- tThe Right Information at the Right Time: Optimizing the Provision of Information to Facilitate the Settlement and Integration of Refugees in Canada -- tThe Alberta Syrian Refugee Project: Understanding Trauma and Resilience in Refugee Resettlement -- tHealth Needs and Service Use of Newly Arrived Syrian Refugees -- tExperiences of Syrian Refugee Children, Youth, and Families -- tThe Honeymoon's Over: Post-Settlement Issues and Challenges for Syrian Refugee Youth in Canada -- tStress in Refugee Resettlement: Syrian Mothers' Strains and Buffers during Early Integration -- tSyrian Refugee Youths' Use of Social Media as a Space for Communicating Social Support during Resettlement -- tThe Syrian Refugee Resettlement Context -- tCivil Society and Community Perspectives and Experiences -- tInterrogating Canada's Response to the Syrian Crisis: Analyzing the Observations of Post-Secondary Youth -- tAccommodating Government-Assisted Syrian Refugee Newcomers: The Experiences of Resettlement Assistance Program Providers -- tPrivate Sponsorship of Syrian Refugees: Perspectives of Sponsors and Refugees in Quebec -- tA Tale of Three Mid-Sized Cities: Syrian Refugee Resettlement and a Progressive Sense of Place -- tReception and Integration in Smaller Cities and Rural Areas -- tSplits in the Neighbourhood? Negotiating Visibility in a Rural Reception Context -- tA Community Engaged in the Reception of Syrian Refugees: The Case of Moncton, New Brunswick -- tSyrian Refugee Integration in Newfoundland and Labrador -- tOutcomes and Lessons from Canada's Experience with the Syrian Refugee Resettlement Initiative -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the outbreak of the Syrian Civil War in 2011, over 5.6 million people have fled Syria and another 6.6 million remain internally displaced. By January 2017, a total of 40,081 Syrians had sought refuge across Canada in the largest resettlement event the country has experienced since the Indochina refugee crisis. Breaking new ground in an effort to understand and learn from the Syrian Refugee Resettlement Initiative that Canada launched in 2015, A National Project examines the experiences of refugees, receiving communities, and a range of stakeholders who were involved in their resettlement, including sponsors, service providers, and various local and municipal agencies. The contributors, who represent a wide spectrum of disciplines, include many of Canada's leading immigration scholars and others who worked directly with refugees. Considering the policy behind the program and the geographic and demographic factors affecting it, chapters document mobilization efforts, ethical concerns, integration challenges, and varying responses to resettling Syrian refugees from coast to coast. Articulating key lessons to be learned from Canada's program, this book provides promising strategies for future events of this kind. Showcasing innovative practices and initiatives, A National Project captures a diverse range of experiences surrounding Syrian refugee resettlement in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Refugees.2bisacsh1 aAgic, Branka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAhmed, Rukhsana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl Saadi, Esra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlghazali, Idris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBajjali, Lubna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelkhodja, Chedly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennett-AbuAyyash, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlain, Marie-Jeanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoucher, Yannick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaron, Roxane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharette, Alexandra G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClaire Neil, Kerri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCullen, Blair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDam, Huyen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrolet, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl Chaar, Dania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel